<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0008 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0046EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-MassachusettsAt-A-Glance     03-08 0277</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Massachusetts At-A-Glance,290</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from Massachusetts to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 98   Super delegates: 11   Total: 109   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Saturday, April 23 and Friday, May 13   Massachusetts Democrats pick national convention delegatesthrough a primary-caucus system.   All of the state's 98 pledged delegates to the DemocraticNational Convention will be allocated among the presidentialcandidates in proportion to the results of the March 8 primary. Thedelegates themselves will be chosen at caucuses and meetings infollowing weeks.   Former House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. automatically will begiven a seat as an unpledged delegate. O'Neill is one of fiveformer Democratic Party leaders nationwide who receive automaticdelegate status.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 52   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Dates not yet determined.   Massachusetts Republicans allocate their national conventiondelegates among presidential candidates in proportion to results ofthe March 8 primary.   All candidates receiving at least 1.923 percent of the statewidevote are eligible to receive delegates.   Allocation of delegates is made by an allocation committee afterthe primary. The congressional district delegates are chosen incaucuses within 60 days of the primary. The at-large delegates areselected by the Republican State Committee within 45 days of thecongressional district caucuses.</TEXT></DOC>